Advertisement CTR Prediction¶

The Advertisement CTR Prediction challenge is to predict the Click-Through Rate (CTR) for advertisements using the dataset 2020-digix-advertisement-ctr-prediction.

The objective of this Jupyter Notebook is to do an Exploratory Data Analysis over the sampling dataset exported in 01-SamplingDataset.ipynb.

Number of Duplicates Rows¶

As we can see below, there is 4.527 duplicated rows, i.e, the values for all columns are the same.

As the number of duplicated rows represents 0.5% of the samples in provided dataset and only 2.34% of samples when users click on ad, the duplicated rows will be delete from dataset.

In [7]:

Distribution of Label column¶

The provided data is categorized as an unbalanced dataset, i.e., there are a lot of samples belongs to label = 0 and few examples belongs to label = 1.

In [11]:
ctr_distribution_df = dataset_df['label'].value_counts().reset_index(name='count')
ctr_distribution_df.rename(columns={'label': 'click_through_indicator'}, inplace=True)

ctr_distribution_df['percentage'] = ctr_distribution_df['count'] / dataset_df.shape[0]

clicked_mask = (dataset_df['label'] == 1).values

Segment Analysis¶

In the graph below the users who belongs to groups 4, 5, 6 and 7 in age columns had the most clicks in ads than users who belongs to groups -1, 1, 2 and 3.¶

This behaviour follow the age column distribution in the whole dataset.¶

In [14]:
age_df = dataset_df['age'].value_counts().reset_index(name='count')
age_df['percentage'] = age_df['count'] / age_df['count'].sum()

users_age_df = dataset_df.loc[clicked_mask, ['age']].value_counts().reset_index(name='n_clicks')
users_age_df['percentage'] = users_age_df['n_clicks'] / clicked_mask.sum()

Segment Analysis: Impact of City¶

In the graph Average Number of Clicks by Users we can see that cities that belongs to city_rank equals to 2 had the most average number os clicks by users.

However, in the graph Average Number of Clicks by Apps the sames group of cities (city_rank equals to 2) had the smaller average number of clicks by apps.

In [21]:
n_users_by_city = dataset_df.groupby(['city'])['uid'].nunique().reset_index(name='n_users')
n_apps_by_city = dataset_df.groupby(['city'])['spread_app_id'].nunique().reset_index(name='n_apps')
n_ctr_by_city = dataset_df[clicked_mask].groupby('city')['label'].count().reset_index(name='n_clicks')
In [22]:
city_stats = dataset_df[['city', 'city_rank']].drop_duplicates()
city_stats = city_stats.merge(n_users_by_city, on='city', how='left')
city_stats = city_stats.merge(n_apps_by_city, on='city', how='left')
city_stats = city_stats.merge(n_ctr_by_city, on='city', how='left')

city_stats['clicks_per_users'] = city_stats['n_clicks'] / city_stats['n_users']
city_stats['clicks_per_apps'] = city_stats['n_clicks'] / city_stats['n_apps']
In [23]:
fig, (axs1, axs2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(24, 6))

clicks_city_rank_users_ax = city_stats.boxplot(by='city_rank', column='clicks_per_users', ax=axs1, rot=0)
clicks_city_rank_users_ax.set_title('Average Number of Clicks by Users')
custom_plot(clicks_city_rank_users_ax)

clicks_city_rank_apps_ax = city_stats.boxplot(by='city_rank', column='clicks_per_apps', ax=axs2, rot=0)
clicks_city_rank_apps_ax.set_title('Average Number of Clicks by Apps')
custom_plot(clicks_city_rank_apps_ax)

plt.tight_layout(w_pad=5)

Correlation Matrix¶

In the matrix below we can infer that:

  • App tag of an ad task (tags) has a stronger positive relation to display form of an ad material (inter_type_cd) - It might suggest that some ad forms are better than others for specific apps
  • App tag of an ad task (tags) has a stronger positive relation to app rating score (app_score) - It might suggest with which ad tasks are used by the more popular apps.
In [24]:
plt.figure(figsize=(30, 30))

corr_matrix = dataset_df[dataset_df.columns.difference(['communication_onlinerate'])].corr()

mask = np.zeros_like(corr_matrix)
mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask)] = True

corr_heatmap = sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, cmap="Blues", annot=True, mask=mask)

Feature Engineering¶

As the values in dataset are encoded it is very complicated apply a feature engineering process.

Because of that, I choose only process the column `` and apply the method OneHotEncoded.

In [25]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder
In [26]:
one = OneHotEncoder(sparse_output=False, handle_unknown='ignore')
communication_onlinerate_encoded = one.fit_transform(dataset_df['communication_onlinerate'].values.reshape(-1, 1))
In [27]:
n_columns = communication_onlinerate_encoded.shape[1]
columns = [f"communication_onlinerate_{str(i).zfill(4)}" for i in range(n_columns)]

communication_onlinerate_encoded_df = pd.DataFrame(communication_onlinerate_encoded, columns=columns, dtype=np.uint8)
In [28]:
dataset_df = dataset_df.join(communication_onlinerate_encoded_df)
In [29]:
dataset_df.drop(columns=['communication_onlinerate'], inplace=True)
